git commits :
-explain what is commit and what happen when its executed
-explain staging area
-explain states of files ,new , staged ,tracked etc
check status of tracked files : git status
check status of files including untracked : git status -u
before commit, we add files to staging area by : git add $fileName
-to add only tracked files and exclude new ones to staging area : git add -u .
-to add all changes at once : git add .
-if you add a modified file, then modify it again , you should add the second change. if you commit without adding the file again , the second change will be lost. 
-after adding files , commit with the command :  git commit -m “message”
-we can also express commit modified tracked files with : git commit -am “message”, this will add and commit them directly (does not include new created files)
-git will not commit new files (untracked files) without adding them first to staging area.
-to unstage files : git restore --staged file_name
-to restore files : git restore file_name
-define difference between git log and reflog and their commands
show information about particular commit : git show <commit id>
-to list signed commits : git log --show-signature
- **Atomic commits:**
💡 when possible a commit should encompass a single feature,change to fix. try to keep each commit focused on a single thing.
